One of my absolute favorite things in life is learning about different countries & cultures so here's 5 interesting facts I learned on this trip to Qatar 🇶🇦 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
- Qatar is the richest country in the world per capita because it's home to the world's third-largest natural gas and oil reserves.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
- Out of 2.5 million people, men outnumber women 3 to 1😳⠀⠀⠀
- 30% of the country's total area is covered by environmental protection which is one of the highest rates in the world.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
- In 2022, Qatar will become the first Arab country to host the FIFA World Cup.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
- The highest altitude is only 343 feet (103 meters).⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
I had the pleasure of visiting so many new places this year, including Qatar. What did you learn about from the places you traveled to this year?😊

What is your favorite country??
I get asked this question constantly! I could never choose just one country because every area of the world is so unique and has something completely different to offer. With that in mind, I just posted a new YouTube video talking about the 5 countries that surprised me the most after traveling to them all! Let me know what you think😊 link is in my bio.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Here's a hint: 🇵🇰 🇪🇬 🇹🇲 🇻🇪 🇮🇸

The past few years have been crazy!! It's been a whirlwind of so many different landscapes and cultures and new lessons learned. Even after traveling to every country it still feels like I've only just begun to scratch the surface of how much there really is out there. I've spent this week reflecting on my favorite places & making the most epic list of dream destinations for 2020 & I'm getting SO EXCITED. What places are at the top of your travel list? 🌏💭🌍

Muchas gracias por el amor de America Latina! Since @cnnee made a fantastic feature about my story I've been so amazed by all the kind messages I've been receiving, especially from one of my absolute favorite places, Venezuela 🇻🇪♥️ Everywhere I went I felt overwhelmed by kindness and hospitality, breathtaking landscapes and dangerously good arepas!🤤 I can't wait to explore more incredible places in Latin America in 2020, let me know where you think I should visit in the comments! Who's already excited to celebrate #Carnival?😉⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Photo by @fearlessandfar & you can see our adventure videos from Venezuela on his Youtube channel!

This was the most beautiful sunrise I've ever seen in my life✨ Couldn't have thought of a more epic way to end the journey up the most dangerous volcano in Africa. The continent of Africa never ceases to amaze me 🌍 I just posted my first ever travel vlog on YouTube from this place, you can find it in the link in my bio!

Travel & relationships are a weird combination🤪 My feed is constantly filled with spectacular photos of travel couples living perfect lives in the most beautiful places. Personally, I'm still trying to understand how those lifestyles work because there's so much more going on than what you see on social media that no one talks about.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Over the past couple years since I started traveling constantly, I've gone through 2 or 3 rough breakups. My schedule is usually so hectic that I've felt 'undateable' and super lonely and isolated at times. You might never think that just looking at my Instagram feed though. Take these photos of Thomas and I in South Korea for example. We genuinely are a happy couple that gets to travel and do fun things together occasionally. But what you don't see is how much we miss each other or get jealous or stressed when the other person is out doing something awesome solo. Being in a relationship and traveling can be great, but it's never as simple & easy as it looks. I just wanted to remind you guys that what you see on here is just what people want you to see, not the full story #couplegoals 😂

Who's ready for winter?❄️ I still can't believe that it's basically December & the end of 2019 is so close! We just had our first snow in Northern California and I'm getting so excited for powder filled snowboarding days and nights spent snuggling up by the fire. Seems like most people either LOVE winter or they absolutely hate it. Which kind of person are you?
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

What did I LEARN from traveling to every country?⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
This is the question that’s been on my mind the most recently. It’s going to take years to unpack everything but here’s a few of my favorite realizations so far:⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
-My favorite places in the world ended up being where I least expected them.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
- I was genuinely surprised how accessible the world felt to me as a young woman.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
-The magic of traveling isn't actually about the place, its about the people who live there & the people you came there with.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
-Traveling to every country made me immensely grateful for so many things, especially for the passport I carry. It reminded me not to take it for granted since so many people don’t have access to the same privileges.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
-You could travel to a completely new place every day for the rest of your life and never run out of things to do.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
-Despite coming from very different environments and growing up with different values and economic situations; I experienced nothing but kindness from the people I encountered all around the world. If anything, it’s the small differences and details that makes discovering new cultures such a beautiful experience. The world would be so boring if everything was the same everywhere! ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
This post was inspired by the YouTube video I'm making right now. If you're interested, go subscribe through the link in my bio. So excited to share it with you😊

ITS OFFICIAL!!🥳 After years of travel, months of planning & mountains of paperwork to prove it- I'm now the Guinness World Record Holder for the Youngest Person to Travel to Every Country!🤩🌍⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
It's been a crazy week celebrating here in NYC & having the Today Show surprise me with this certificate yesterday was literally a dream come true. I've been spending a lot of time reflecting on what I've taken away from traveling to 196 countries & honestly I feel like I've only just scratched the surface of how much there is to explore! Traveling to all these places around the world taught me that countries aren't as black and white as lines on the map. There's actually this beautiful, interconnected tapestry of cultures, beliefs and landscapes that blend together to create this strange & wonderful world we live in.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
It's been such an honor & a privilege to experience so much and to share this journey with all of you. I definitely couldn't have done it without the many special people I encountered along the way. I'm feeling grateful for all the lessons learned & I'm SO EXCITED FOR WHAT'S NEXT🥂 go to the link in my bio to subscribe to my brand new YOUTUBE CHANNEL!

In 2005 hurricane Katrina hit the coast of Louisiana, destroying everything in its path with catastrophic flooding. The total damage from the hurricane is estimated to be around $160 billion. Just one of the places that was abandoned after the flooding was this Six Flags amusement park just outside the city. It was such an eerie feeling walking around a place that was once filled with so much color & life.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Also (if you haven't already noticed) I'm EXTREMELY afraid of heights and when we climbed to the top of an abandoned roller coaster, I was FREAKING OUT. Check out Epic Exploring on Insight TV for the full story😆

My face when the camera crew tells me to hold an alligator's mouth shut with one hand😅 Apparently all of the alligator's jaw power is in the down stroke & they have almost no muscle power when it comes to opening their jaws... or at least that's the theory 😂 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Swipe over to see a huge gator aptly named Brutus & to get a glimpse of how beautiful the Bayou is in Louisiana. I'll never get over how diverse the landscapes are in the US✨

I have a confession to make... ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
I'm a HUGE fan of taking naps. I've been known to squeeze in a nap whenever, wherever possible. This has been very advantageous when sleeping on planes but I'll admit it's hard to control while in beautiful places. But let's be honest- this was a pretty epic place for a nap! I love curling up and sleeping in the sun so much, I think I might have been a cat in my past life. ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

Do you ever go through phases where you don't want to post anything?🤪⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
I'm STRUGGLING with how I want to use this platform which is annoying because I didn't used to take it so seriously! Sometimes I have the urge to overshare in hopes that it might be relatable to someone. Other times I want to create a little barrier between this place and my real life because I don't always like the way it makes me feel. I feel vulnerable and frustrated but at the same time so grateful to have people's attention and feel a responsibility to share meaningful sh*t. Maybe I'm just overthinking the whole process, it's felt good to take a break from Instagram and focus more on being creative. Maybe I need to plan another trip somewhere crazy so I can be more excited to share content again. Or maybe I should just start making more jokes😆 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Photo by @angelanunnink

Isn't it CRAZY that places like this still exist?? ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
When I came here, this place was almost completely empty and there were no other foreign visitors in sight. It felt like such an intense contrast since millions of tourists flock to countries like Greece and Italy every year to see ruins of ancient civilizations just like Leptis Magna. Libya has such a rich and well preserved history that not very many people get the opportunity to travel to because it can be risky to travel here. I'm grateful that this time, the risk was definitely worth the reward 🙏🏼 🇱🇾 I’d loved to hear any of your suggestions for really unusual or more unknown places I should consider traveling to next year🌍

Last week I went on a surprise trip to Mozambique to bring school supplies to a bunch of kids, let me tell you about it. ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Over 3 months ago I submitted all 6,500+ pages of my application in chronological order to Guinness World Records for the youngest person to travel to every country. After lots of back and forth, they decided that my visit to Mozambique in 2018 wouldn't count for my record because I didn't use public transportation. Last time I went to Mozambique was on a road trip with a friend who drove me from Eswatini (#Swaziland) to the border of #Mozambique. From the thick book of strict GWR guidelines, apparently you can't take a private car into a country. While this was a frustrating technicality, I went back to Mozambique to clear it up. On the bright side, it didn't really change anything since I'm still 21 and broke the record by over 3 years😊⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀
To make the most out of this return trip, I gathered a bunch of school supplies to bring with me to Mozambique in hopes of finding some kids who could use them. By complete coincidence, I met 3 incredibly kind Portuguese guys on the flight to Maputo who happened to be volunteering at an orphanage outside of the city. Within 48 hours of leaving California without a plan, I found myself in the middle of nowhere with a bunch of people I've never met & hundreds of smiling kids. This impromptu trip reminded me how spontaneous travel can be & how you never really know where you're going to end up when you start out on an adventure😊

Nothing says "sit and stay a while" like a rolling alpine meadow adorned with a turquoise lake✨ places like this always remind me how small I am in this world 🌎 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

I’ve always loved Mythology. I even took a class on it in college. One of my favorite series of myths has always been the ones about the trickster demigod Maui (even before Moana came out, I promise 😉).
The legend goes that Maui once set out to capture the sun and convince it to slow down. One night Maui journeyed to the peak of the mountain Haleakalā (which actually means house of the sun) and waited for the sun to wake up and rise from its crater. Details differ from legend to legend, but as soon as the sun showed itself that morning, storytellers agree that Maui swung a lasso around the sun! He allowed the sun to go free only after it agreed to travel more slowly through the sky for half the year. Thus the seasons were born, with shorter days in the winter and longer days in the summer. Happy fall everyone!🍂 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Do you have any favorite myths?⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

The Top 5 Regrets Of The Dying:
1. I wish I'd had the courage to live a life true to myself, not the life others expected of me. 
2. I wish I hadn't worked so hard. 
3. I wish I'd had the courage to express my feelings. 
4. I wish I had stayed in touch with my friends.
5. I wish that I had let myself be happier. By @bronnie.ware⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
This list has been on my mind a lot lately. It's the reason I make the majority of the decisions in my life based on the answer to a very simple question- will I regret not doing this? I’m learning to enjoy each moment exactly as it is, not comparing it to yesterday or tomorrow or what someone else is doing. The best and worst part of life is that nothing lasts forever.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
